Chapter 2

- HTML structure
    
    ¬†****`<!DOCTYPE html>`¬†**- it declares that the document is html (instruction to the user to use html)**
    
    ALL html files must start with `<!DOCTYPE html>` and <html> elements
    
    example: 
    
    ```html
    <!DOCTYPE html> <!-- doesnt need a closing tag -->
    <html> <!-- needs a closing tag as it should contain <head> and <body> -->
      Code goes here
    </html>
    ```
    
    example 2:
    
    ```html
    <!DOCTYPE html>
    <html>
      <head>
        Some code goes here
      </head>
      <body>
        A lot more goes here
      </body>
    </html>
    ```
    
    the <title> element is featured in the <head>
    
    ```html
    <!DOCTYPE html>
    <html>
      <head>
        <title>Cod√©dex | Start your coding adventure ‚ãÜÀô‚ü°</title> 
        <!-- this assigns the title to the tab -->
      </head>
      <body>
        Code goes here <!-- all the main code is featured here -->
      </body>
    </html> 
    ```
    
    ![image.png](image.png)
    
    - coding question
        
        ```html
        <!-- Write code below üíñ -->
        <!DOCTYPE html>
        <html>
        <head>
        <title> Coding with Java </title>
        </head>
        <body>
        <p> this is how you code! </p>
        <p> bla bla bla bla </p>
        </body>
        </html>
        ```
        
- Family Tree
    
    elements in a html file are much arranged like a family tree
    
    - **Parent and child elements**
        
        ```html
        <!DOCTYPE html>
        <html>
          <head> <!-- child of html -->
            <title>My Website</title> <!-- child of head -->
          </head>
          <body> <!-- child of html -->
            <p>Well, <i><!-- child of p -->howdy</i> there!</p>
          </body>
        </html>
        ```
        
    - Sibling elements
        
        ```html
        <body>
          <ul>
            <li>üçÑ Mario</li> <!--sibling elements as their both children to <ul>-->
        		<li>üê¢ Luigi</li> <!--sibling elements as their both children to <ul>-->
          </ul>
        </body>
        ```
        
    - coding question
        
        ```html
        <!-- Write code below üíñ -->
        <!DOCTYPE html>
        <html>
          <body>
            <head>
              <title> My Family Tree </title>
            </head>
              <h1> My Family Tree </h1>
        <p> Parents: </p> <ul>
        <li> Ron </li>
        <li> Jon </li>
        <li> Bon </li>
        </ul>
        
        <p> Children from oldest to youngest: </p> <ol>
        <li> Natt </li>
        <li> Bruce </li>
        <li> Layla </li>
        </ol>
          </body>
        </html>
        ```
        
- Comments
    
    comments should be used sparingly and removed when no longer needed 
    
    ```html
    <!-- -->
    ```
    
    Types of Comments
    
    - Inline
        
        ```html
         <p>This text is visible. <!-- But this is not. --></p>
        ```
        
    - Multi-line
        
        ```html
        <!--
          This is also a comment.
          HI
          YAAA
        -->
        ```
        
- Attributes
    
    they provide **additional information** about the elements in a line of code
    
    they‚Äôre usually **name/value** pairs (`name="value"`)
    
    exmaple: ¬†****
    
    ```html
    <img src="dog.jpg">
    <!-- src is the name of the attribute
    
    "dog.jpg" is the value-->
    ```
    
    - coding example (generally explains attributes)
        
        ```html
        <!-- for example this ordered list automatically 
        becomes ordered by numbers -->
        
        <ol>
          <li>Power ‚ö°</li>
          <li>Courage üî•</li>
          <li>Wisdom ü¶â</li>
        </ol>
        
        <!-- we can change that with attributes -->
        
        <ol type="a"> <!-- now the list will be ordered in 
        alphabetical order starting with "a"  -->
          <li>Power ‚ö°</li>
          <li>Courage üî•</li>
          <li>Wisdom ü¶â</li>
        </ol>
        
        ```
        
    - coding exampe (attributes in image tag)
        
        ```html
         <img src="https://i.imgur.com/TrXO7Sa.png" width="250">
        
        <!-- "src" and "width="250" are an examples 
        of attributes -->
        
        <img alt="pixel girl using a laptop" src 
        ="https://www.codedex.io/images/tier1.png">
        
        <!-- 2 attributes featured src and alt -->
        <!-- "alt" is an attribute -->
        <!-- if the image can't be shown, the alt text is shown instead -->
        ```
        
    - coding example (attribute in anchor tag)
        
        ```html
        <a href="https://www.codedex.io/">Cod√©dex</a>
        <!-- "href" is an attribute, where the link goes -->
        
        <a href="https://www.codedex.io/" target="_blank">Cod√©dex</a>
        
        <!-- this target="_blank" attribute can be added  to make 
        the link open in a new browser tab-->
        ```
        
    - coding question using alt text and new tab link
        
        ```html
        <!DOCTYPEhtml>
        <html>
        <head>
        <title> Wiki Article of Albert Einstein </title>
        </head>
        <body>
        <h1> The Hero: Albert Einstein </h1>
        <img alt = "This picture features his goofy side" src= "https://hips.hearstapps.com/hmg-prod/images/albert-einstein-sticks-out-his-tongue-when-asked-by-news-photo-1681316749.jpg">
        <p> He was a theoretical physicist. He was well known for developing the theory of relativity.</p>
        <a href = "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Einstein" target "_blank"> Wiki on Albert </a>
        
        </body>
        </html>
        ```
        
    - Attributes 2
        
        classes and ids , any element can use these attributes
        
        - ids
            
            identifies an element
            
            can be used to link another part of the same page (e.g. the heading)
            
            example:
            
            ```html
            <a href="#medellin">Link to Medell√≠n</a>
            
            <h2 class="city" id="medellin">Medell√≠n üá®üá¥</h2>
            ```
            
            when referencing a section to go to, like a url a hashtag is used
            
            ```html
            <a href="#section1">Go to Section 1</a>
            <!-- this shows that if the person clicks this, they'll 
            be brought to section 1 -->
            
            ```
            
            however, a hashtag is not used when assigning an id to an element
            
            ```html
            <div id="section1">...</div> <!-- No # here -->
            
            ```
            
        - classes
            
            grouping elements under a common theme
            
            - non coding example
                
                
                | Element | Class |  |
                | --- | --- | --- |
                | Geometry | Math |  |
                | Algebra | Math |  |
        - Differences
            
            An **element** can be assigned to **multiple class values**
            
            (In other words‚Ä¶Multiple Classes can have the same element)
            
            ```html
            <p class="first-value second-value third-value">Hello, World</p>
            ```
            
            HOWEVER
            
            An element can only have one id value
            
            (In other words, An id can only be given to one element)
            
            ```html
            <p id="value">Hello, World</p>
            ```
            
        
        ALWAYS **LOWERCASE**
        
        if the names of the attributes have multiple words, they should be separated with ‚Äú-‚Äù
        
        - Division Element
            
            When creating sections in html we use the element <div> (short for division)
            
            groups elements
            
            - example in coding:
                
                ```html
                <div class="page-section" id="about-me"> <!-- it is combined with 
                                                         the class and id attributes -->
                  <h2>About Me</h2>
                  <p>Ness is an aspiring web developer!</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="page-section" id="social-media">
                  <h2>Social:</h2>
                  <ul>
                    <li>GitHub</li>
                    <li>Twitter</li>
                    <li>LinkedIn</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
                ```
                
