                </body>
                </html>
                ```
                
    - Style Attribute
        
        we can create a style to our html code to make our text look more fun!
        
        - code example:
            
            ```html
            <p>
              Roses are <span style="color:red;">red</span>.<br />
              Violets are <span style="color:blue;">blue</span>.
            </p>                  <!--property "color" and a value "red"
                                        separated by colon-->
                                        
            <!-- when listing multiple styles, they have to be separated 
            with a semicolon -->
            
            <p>
              Roses are <span style="color:red; text-decoration:underline;">red</span>.<br />
              Violets are <span style="color:blue; text-decoration:underline;">blue</span>.
            </p>
            
            ```
            
        - styling the <body>:
            
            ```html
            <!DOCTYPE html>
            <html>
              <head>
                <style>
                  ... Styles for elements go here
                </style>
              </head>
              <body>
                ... Elements go here
              </body>
            </html>
            ```
            
        - styling certain elements:
            
            ```html
            <style>
              element {
                property: value;
              }
            </style>
            ```
            
        - everything put together:
            
            ```html
            <!DOCTYPE html>
            <html>
              <head>
                <style>
                  span {
                    text-decoration: underline;
                  }         <--! in a style element, you can use a . (class) or 
                                    hashtag to select elements-->
            
                  #red-word {
                    color: red;
                  }
            
                  #blue-word {
                    color: blue;
                  }
                </style>
              </head>
              <body>
                <p>
                  Roses are <span id="red-word">red</span>.<br />
                  Violets are <span id="blue-word">blue</span>.<br />
                </p>
              </body>
            </html>
            ```
            
- Forms
    
    collects user input data
    
    how they work:
    
    1. **The user enters some information.**
    2. **The user presses a ‚ÄúSubmit‚Äù button.**
    3. **And something happens!**
    - 2 attributes are commonly used in form
        1. Action = where the form of the data goes after submitted
        2. method = how the form data is processed 
- Inputs
    
    <input> used as a control for measuring data 
    
    <type> kind of input
    
    ```html
    <form>
      <input type="text"> <!-- renders plain text -->
    ```
    
    </form>
    
    <submit> turns to the <input> into a button for submitting the form data
    
    ```html
    <form>
      <input type="submit">
    </form>
    ```
    
- Input Validation
    
    how do we make sure that the input a user types i valid to our code?
    
    we can use code like
    
    ```html
    <input = "password" minlength= "5" maxlegth= "10">
    
    <!-- This will make sure the user types a password
    thats minimum length 5 letters and max 10.. if not.. 
    the password isnt valid-->
    ```
    
- 17) Required Data
    
    data which needs to be submitted 
    
    ```html
    <form method="dialog">
      Name: <input type="text" required> <!-- only required -->
      <br><br>
      Favorite Color: <input type="text">
      <input type="submit">
    </form>
    ```
    
- Inputting Numbers
    
    ```html
    <input type= "number">
    ```
    
    arrows appear automatically in this code
    
    for the arrows to skip to steps : e.g. (-2,0,2,4,6)
    
    ```html
    <input type= "number" step= "2">
    ```
    
    if you want the minimum number to be 5 and the max 10 you can set your code up like this:
    
    ```html
    <input type= "number" minimum= "5" maximum= "10">
    ```
    
- Inputting Checkboxes
    
    ```html
    <input type = "checkbox"> Action
    ```
    
- Inputting Radio and giving names
    
    ```html
    <input type = "radio"> Thank
    <input type = "radio"> Goodness!
    
    ```
    
- How to make the user choose only one input
    
    ```html
    before:
    <input type = "radio"> Thank
    <input type = "radio"> Goodness!
    
    after:
    <input type = "radio" name= "option"> Thank
    <input type = "radio" name= "option"> Goodness!
    ```
    
- 19 Text areas
    
    another text input in forms are ‚Äútext areas‚Äù
    
    ```html
    <textarea id="data-entry" rows="7" cols="42"  placeholder="Enter some data here!">
    </textarea>
    
    ```
    
    as the elements <class> and <id> use <rows>, <cols> (columns) and <placeholder>  so does <textarea>
    
- Form Labels
    
    labels can be used in forms
    
    - e.g.
        
        ```html
        <form>
          <label>Book Title: </label><input type="text">
          <br><br>
          <label>Author: </label><input type="text">
          <br><br>
          <input type="submit">
        </form>
        ```
        
    
    how to associate label to different to different elements on a form
    
    ```html
    <form>
      <label for="title">Book Title: </label><input type="text" id="title">
      <br><br>
      <label for="author" >Author: </label><input type="text" id="author">
      <br><br>
      <input type="submit">
    </form>
    ```
    
    ```html
    <form>
      <label>Book Title: <input type="text"></label>
      <label>Author: <input type="text"></label>
    </form>
    ```
    
- coding question using text areas and form labels
    
    ```html
    <!DOCTYPE html>
    <html>
      <head>
        <title>Contact Us</title>
      </head>
      <body>
        <form>
      <h2>Contact Us</h2>
      <label> Name: </label> <input type= "text">
      <br><br>
      <label> Comments and suggestions: </label> 
      <br>
      <textarea id= rows= "40" cols= "30" placeholder= "enter here"></textarea>
      <br><br>
      <input type= "submit">
    </form>
      </body>
    </html>
    ```
    
- What version of html do we use today
    
    HTML5
    
- Semantic elements
    
    semantic is more meaningful than using other elements like ‚Äúdiv‚Äù or ‚Äúspan‚Äù to structure code
    
    they improve the understanding of code between human readers and machines
    
    enhance SEO (search engine optimization?
    
    - difference between non semantic code and semantic code
        
        non semantic code
        
        ```html
        <div>
          <div>My Blog Title</div>
          <div>Some blog content here...</div>
        </div>
        
        ```
        
        semantic code
        
        ```html
        <article>
          <header>My Blog Title</header>
          <p>Some blog content here...</p>
        </article>
        
        ```
        
    - common semantic elements
        
        
        | Element | Purpose |
        | --- | --- |
        | `<header>` | Defines the **introductory content** or navigation of a page/section |
        | `<nav>` | Contains **navigation links** |
        | `<main>` | Contains the **main content** of the page (only one per page) |
        | `<section>` | Groups related content into a **section** with a heading |
        | `<article>` | Represents **independent, self-contained content**, like blog posts |
        | `<aside>` | Contains **sidebar content** or content tangentially related |
        | `<footer>` | Contains the **footer** of a page or section (contact, copyright, etc.) |
        | `<figure>` | Used to group **media** (images, charts) with a caption |
        | `<figcaption>` | The **caption** for the `<figure>` element |
        | `<mark>` | Highlights text as **important or relevant** |
        | `<time>` | Represents a **time or date** |
    

---

Chapter 3 semantic element

- Header (not head) <header>
    
    <header> </header>
    
    - example
        
        ```html
        <body>
          <header> <!-- in the body -->
            <h1>Welcome to My Site!</h1> <!-- uses heading elements 
            h1 to h6 -->
          </header>
        </body>
        ```
        
    
    the header includes information like:
    
    - the website logo
    - title of the site
    - search bar
    - other links to other areas of the site
    - sign in button
- Navigation <nav>
    
    To go to other links/pages on the header, you need to use navigation
    
    <nav> which goes inside the header
    
    - example
        
        ```html
        <header>
          <nav>
            <!-- Links go here -->
          </nav> <!-- can contain ordered and unordered lists -->
        </header>
        ```
        
- coding question #1 (header, nav)
    
    ```html
    <!DOCTYPE html>
    <html>
      <head>
        <title>Blogging with Jaycee</title>
      </head>
      <body>
        <header>
          <h1> Welcome to my blog "Blogging with Jaycee"... </h1>
        <nav>
          <ul>
            <li> <a href= "#about-section"> About </a> </li>
            <li> <a href="#story-section"> Stories </a> </li>
          </ul>
        </nav>
        </header>
      </body>
    </html>
    
    ```
    
- main and footer <main>
    
    <main> - main topics and ideas shown on page 
    
    - coding example
        
        ```html
        <body>
          <main>
            <!-- Main information goes here -->
          </main>
        </body>
        ```
        
    
    <footer> - goes beneath the main content of the page.. it includes.. the name of the company, copyright info and additional links to other sections of the website or other websites.
    
    - coding example
        
        ```html
        <footer>
          <!-- Footer content goes here -->
        </footer>
        ```
        
- coding question #2 (header, nav, main and footer)
    
    ```html
    <!-- Write code below üíñ -->
    <!DOCTYPE html>
    <html>
      <head>
        <title>Blogging with Jaycee</title>
      </head>
      <body>
        <header>
          <h1> Welcome to my blog "Blogging with Jaycee"... </h1>
        <nav>
          <ul>
            <li> <a href= "#about-section"> About </a> </li>
            <li> <a href="#story-section"> Stories </a> </li>
          </ul>
        </nav>
        </header>
        <main> 
        <h2> HTML BLOG </h2>
        </main>
        <footer> 
          <ul>
            <li> <a href= "#archive"> Archives </li>
            <li> <a href= "#legal"> Legal </li>
          </ul>
    
        </footer>
      </body>
    </html>
    
    ```
    
- page sections <section>
    
    groups related content together 
    
    within the page, there are smaller parts which are called sections 
    
    <section>
    
    - coding example
        
        ```html
        <main>
          <section>
            <h2>Section A</h2>
          </section>
          <section>
            <h2>Section B</h2>
          </section>
          <section>
            <h2>Section C</h2>
          </section>
        </main>
        ```
        
- single articles <article>
    
    singular pieces of content 
    
    - coding example
        
        ```html
        <section>
          <h2>Section Heading</h2>
          <article>
            <h3>Article Heading</h3>
            Piece of content
          </article>
        </section>
        ```
        
- figures <figure>
    
    a figure is usually a graphic, image or diagram.
    
    - coding example
        
        ```html
        <figure>
          <!-- Figure content goes here -->
        </figure>
        ```
        
    - captioning figures
        
        using <figcaption> to describe what‚Äôs in <figure>
        
        - example
            
            ```html
            <figure>
              <img
                width="500"
                src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Tsunami_by_hokusai_19th_century.jpg/1024px-Tsunami_by_hokusai_19th_century.jpg"
                alt="Great Wave off Kanagawa by Hokusai"
              />
              <figcaption>The Great Wave Off Kanagawa by Hokusai</figcaption>
            </figure>
            ```
            
    
- summary of all the elements we‚Äôve learnt
    
    ```html
    <body>
      <header>
        <nav></nav>
      </header>
      <main>
        <section>
          <article>
            <figure>
              <figcaption></figcaption>
            </figure>
          </article>
        </section>
      </main>
      <footer></footer>
    </body>
    ```
